{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632003"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:35:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:35:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17414"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17414"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10104"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70526"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10104"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55990"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5539"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23672"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70526"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPublic health interventions sometimes require restrictions on individual freedoms to protect community health. During the COVID-19 pandemic, many jurisdictions implemented various public health measures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the concept of liberty in the context of public health?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Unrestricted access to all health services","Prioritisation of individual choice over community needs","Complete freedom from all restrictions","Balance between individual rights and collective wellbeing","Absence of government involvement in health decisions"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that liberty in public health represents a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebalance between individual rights and collective wellbeing\u003C/strong\u003E. This recognises that while personal freedom is important, it must sometimes be limited to protect public health and safety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete freedom from all restrictions\u003C/strong\u003E represents an absolute view of liberty that is impractical in organised society and could harm public health.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrioritisation of individual choice over community needs\u003C/strong\u003E would undermine essential public health measures needed to protect population health.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsence of government involvement in health decisions\u003C/strong\u003E ignores the necessary role government plays in protecting public health through regulation and intervention.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnrestricted access to all health services\u003C/strong\u003E confuses liberty with unlimited access to services, which is not practically achievable.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPublic health measures like vaccination requirements, quarantine during outbreaks, and food safety regulations demonstrate how individual liberties may be reasonably restricted to protect community health.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Liberty is the state of being free within society from oppressive restrictions imposed by authority on one\u0027s way of life, behaviour, or political views.","The concept of liberty encompasses both positive liberty (freedom to) and negative liberty (freedom from).","Public health measures often require balancing individual liberty with collective wellbeing."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55990"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17414"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55990"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T19:00:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T00:10:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10104"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70526"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5326"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":nul